barriers_open: There is mixed messaging around how to access mental health services on this campus. When I arrived it used to be 3 free sessions per semester (even though in practice, this was never followed and was open to the clinician's discretion). I only am aware of mental health resources because of my involvement in this advocacy space, but otherwise I do not think the average student is aware or knowledgeable enough about mental health services and policies surrounding them. There is also the issue of accessibility where someone is not able to get immediate access to counseling if they need it. Although CAPS is revising their counseling structure to accommodate more students, there is still ways to go in regards to getting students the help they need as well as an efficient referral system to other resources/services that can meet other issues/different severities.

barriers_open: The process of navigating insurance barriers is highly discouraging. With suboptimal insurance, finding a provider, especially with the competition there is for mental health services in this area, is next to impossible. As someone who can be, when motivated, resilient when faced with obstacles/barriers, I have been shocked by the level of difficulty it has taken me to find support. 'Difficult' is an understatement. The 'available providers' lists given by insurance companies are rarely (if ever) updated. The majority of clinicians do not respond, do not have availability as is specified by the providers list, and the process becomes 'a numbers game' in that services found, I'd imagine, are correlated to how 'thick your skin can be' due to the absurd amount of rejection/resistance one must face to receive any type of treatment. Regarding University Healthcare Services, the price that is charged to students in need is obscene. For those of us lucky enough to be on the bottom rungs of society, we're expected to fork over ~3-4k yearly when government programs exist that are free? Financial aid money, which already isn't anywhere near enough to manage finances in this area (a 1 bedroom apartment is 2100-2400 monthly not including the barrage of other expenses needed to survive), shouldn't be a considered 'a luxury to have' within the budget that's provided. I have had to repeatedly find alternative health care access--not because I've wanted to--but due to the excessive cost of services provided and the severe financial burden this area puts on most students.

barriers_15_TEXT: I was advised to continue therapy by the counsellor I was seeing but CAPS only provides short-term counselling which I believe would not sufficiently address my circumstances (incidents of domestic violence, family issues, etc.). I am reluctant to seek external support due to concerns about cost and providers understanding my background as an international student.
barriers_open: As previously mentioned, the long-term counselling that I have come to believe would be beneficial/ appropriate for my situation (domestic violence, emotional abuse, family issues, and more) seems to be inaccessible, both in terms of campus resources as well as financially. As an international student, I am also concerned about the whether health care providers in the US would truly understand my cultural and social background, and their influence on the issues I would like to address. While considering external long-term support, navigating using my parents’ financial support to cope with issues they play a part in has been difficult, which is only supplemented by the guilt of non-resident supplemental tuition. Previously, school authority figures who I had close relationships with had been entirely ignorant and/ or dismissive of the help I was receiving from the school counsellor. My parents, who were aware of the situation, also invalidated the work the counsellor and I were doing and treated the impact of the issues I was dealing with as something to blame me for. Additionally, the time commitment mental health care requires seems an intimidating undertaking as a freshman and someone who has had mental health significantly affect academic progress in the past.
